Then a quick and colourful trip to Palm Beach for @kbshowhouse where I was also able to spend some more quality time with my dear friend @joymoylerinteriors Our instant friendship was forged in Cancun. Creative spaces by @philipgorrivan @noznozawa were among my faves but every single room had something special to share.

I often wonder what stories an old ware holds and what it meant to the owner. Was it proudly displayed on a shelf or tucked away and forgotten in a box? The value is often one of perspective and to treasure hunt, in its truest sense, is to seek out the meaningful. 
A watercolor on old paper and signed by an unknown artist can be a seen as a masterpiece for its beauty and the musings it may conjure. A box of crystal prisms, some cloudy with age, could have once adorned a great palace. Perhaps they were once part of a Versailles chandelier!
Somewhere in between antiquity and imagination the treasures lie. 
My time at the Paris Saint-Ouen Flea Market, was short and wondrous. Comprising some 2,500 stores, spread across 15 markets, it's the largest place for treasure hunting in the world! I could have wandered for days dreaming with wide eyes and joyous heart.
The treasures were many. Some were quirky little odds and ends that I found amusing and the multiples of simple items showed themselves as beguiling patterns and sculpture. Art Deco luminaires hung, disparate and glorious, from metal grids and I was drawn in by brightly-hued chairs of the mid-century modern times. 
 I did walk away with a small bag holding the most beautiful watercolor signed by an unknown artist. 
Until next time...

Sunday Places Notebook: My Last Day in Paris

It feels like so long ago and so far away; a world away when I walked along the narrow side streets of Saint-Germain-des-Prés. The January morning was brisk and sunny on this last day in Paris and I wanted to explore. I only had a little over an hour before leaving for the airport, so I skipped my long breakfast (a personal ritual) and ventured out into the already bustling city. 

I did not walk far before stopping at a beautiful door, and then another, and another. 

The streets were lined with them; bold entrances saturated with rich colour and ornament that stirred the imagination to what beauty must lie behind them. Their hardware and large ornate knockers (door furniture as I like to refer to them) had stories to tell within each metal turn.

But I had to divert and keep walking. I wanted to visit some of the antique shops (there are many in this area) and possibly find that one last piece of Paris to bring home with me. I did not walk far before looking through a shop window. Yes, I was intrigued with the rather unusual and somewhat whimsical lamps. I’m sure they were worth a small fortune, but they were just fanciful to me.

Window shopping is a layered experience to me. I love to see the city’s reflection mixed within the wares. Architecture and street signs and grand candelabras; I want to buy the scene. And I do, with a few captures that stir my imagination each time I look back. 

I did not walk far before the narrow streets opened and the River Seine offered the Louvre that stretches endlessly along its banks. 

A world away it seems.

Free Meter Poetry

A diptych of vivid, watery strokes. Simple form in repetition. They play in soft symphony along a sleek french-polished console. 

Two gilded trays offer clear cylinders holding colourful blooms that dance and then bow into graceful poses.

A lamp of polished nickel stands large and fluid; hovering, it seems, between solid and liquid state. 

These beautiful things animate a classical space; melodic counterpoints to the structured.

A plaster ceiling of clean, geometric sculpturing. Tailored chairs around a commanding walnut table. A striking crystal-winged chandelier. They are the clear sonorous voices. 

Those innate complimentary parts; the congruence of variety and unity are a  necessity in art and design, just as free meter in poetry or polyphony in music.   

~ Regina Sturrock

Quiet Luxury. (Volume on to hear my intro) 
This is a primary suite that connects function and beauty within a pared back envelope.  Seamless integration is the key. Take a closer look at unique elements such as the white lacquered dressing hall with floor to ceiling storage behind panels with sleek reveals and illumination. Chevron-patterned hardwood ground this entry. 
It opens its glossy doors to a perfectly aligned central feature; a free-standing tub of pure form under a large window with slim black mullions. This light-filled ensuite is a room of balance, symmetry, and quiet harmony reflecting the classical order of the home. It is also a room that allows exquisite materials to play out on clean structure bringing to effect, a refined contemporary vibe. Warm grey rift-cut oak and white polished gables juxtapose beautifully on the 
vanity wall. It’s a tailored composition that is equally dramatic. Uninterrupted marble slabs make luxury statements framing windows and wrapping walls, floors, and counters. The polished material continues to perform on a built-in console behind the tub that pierces the shower and steps down to form a bench.
Within this tightly integrated envelope there is little available wall space, but lighting takes on the role of modern art. A clean geometry of soft white globes suspended in front of large illuminated mirrors and a ceiling pendant resembling a multi-faceted diamond outcrop are unique elements to appreciate. The final image introduces the bedroom with a dynamic display of faceted illuminated hoops by @matthew.mccormick against an indigo ceiling.

Q: If your focus is on new builds - how does the vision for the entire project take shape?

A: We always take cues from the architecture and tradition of the home and we ensure that there’s a common thread that binds all together with the Client’s needs, wants and 
individualism. That said, our process begins with a solid understanding of the client’s 
lifestyle (what makes them tick) and how that knowledge will translate into the layouts and unfolding of the details such as millwork (cabinetry) and special features. Are they wine collectors, for example, that may warrant a beautiful wine wall? Are there chefs in the family or do they eat out mostly or entertain where they invite caterers or chefs to do the cooking for them. 

Before we design any details, we gather our Client’s feedback through comprehensive questionnaires, particularly where it involves millwork design so that we can truly create a couture ensemble. Kitchens, bathrooms, mudrooms, and dressing rooms are some key areas where we delve into the requirements and idiosyncratic wants all in the name of getting it right. 

We put a strong emphasis on communicating the design vision as well! We paint the picture for our clients through not only detailed working drawings but also with beautifully illustrated renderings that show the entire space in full context with the details, unique materials, and the statement lighting. 

This is when the emotion of the project comes to light for the first time. I love seeing the reactions because our Clients can now fully visualize what we’ve been passionately
developing. Of course, this design has been guided by them along the way so there are no surprises; just excitement knowing that we are steps closer to realizing a common goal of beauty. Examples of our work and process …ours is a couture approach. Take a look through the years of ‘Our Process’ in IG Highlights showing how we do things at RSD.

This Old Door

This old door
Wise soul 
Who has weathered the storms 
Been kissed by morning’s first rays
And veiled by moon’s knowing glow 
Spirited soul 
Who has watched them come and go
Seen first kisses 
Under luna’s love magic 
Storyteller 
Who can spin sweet poetry 
Out of each dense paint layer
And raw plank 
That once glowed with rosy veneer
Old soul 
Who dons its hardware of verdigris 
Burnished by day’s working hands
And coloured by youthful grasps 
In expectation of all that lies ahead
Beautiful 
This old door

The Poetry of Red

"Red is the great clarifier - bright and revealing. I can't imagine becoming bored with red - it would be like becoming bored with the person you love."- Diana Vreeland

One morning in the Menilmontant neighborhood of Paris, a young boy, named Pascal, is on his way to school when he discovers a beautiful and spherical red helium balloon tied to a lamppost. He frees the balloon and the story begins. It's a sentient and mute red balloon following him wherever he goes, floating along the streets of Paris, into the boy's classroom and hovering patiently outside of his bedroom window. 

A beautiful friendship is forged and the pair are inseparable. They draw long, inquisitive looks from adults and they quickly become the envy of the neighbourhood children who are intent on destroying the balloon. 

I first watched 'The Red Balloon' in my grade school classroom. With a musical score and almost no dialogue, the classic 1956 fantasy film is one of images and tender sentiment. It's an allegory for life's love found and lost; of dreams and reinvention. I remember it vividly.

I suppose I have been entranced by the colour red from this point forward. 

The poetry of red lies in its mysticism and its clarity. Primitive, courageous, impulsive, and intense, it can evoke powerful emotion. 

There is a distinctive and confident elegance in the colour red.

Against gallery white walls and, particularly, amid classical architecture, it can be resplendent.    

In fashion the red dress is both confident and alluring. 

The layered patina of a red door, textured and vibrant and full of character, or a succession of red shutters on an olde world facade add more lines to the prose. 

Today’s personal journey of red started with the memory of one mute balloon. It ends with an intense photographic capture of many balloons suspended in full red bloom from the Belle-Epoque dome in Galeries Lafayette, Paris. Photographer, Rebecca Plotnick, believes in getting lost in the Parisian streets without a map. I suspect  a red balloon guided her and pulled her camera in. 

-Regina Sturrock

Uncovering Beauty at the Nizuc
 
It was a powerfully immersive experience of inspiration and joy at the Nizuc Resort and Spa in Cancun, all the while uncovering beauty through the grand and molecular schemes.

This was the second edition of @cosentinousa C.Next Desinger Summit; a gathering of creatives in paradise. I was fortunate to attend both the inaugural and this year’s memorable events.

In 2022, I was on the stage where we delved into home harmony and wellness through intentional design. To me, it speaks to our spiritual/intuitive connections with nature and beauty and the effects of what we perceive as beautiful on our well-being. When we design for health and wellness then it is to the recognition of beauty.

This year, the conversation took on more layers through
discussions around outdoor living environments, old world craft, and seeing (and feeling) beauty through our greatest muse, nature.

Nestled in the enclaves of the mangroves, the NIZUC speaks the language of beauty. Blending a wealth of natural materials with modern technology, the finest Mexican art, and Mayan heritage, the hotel brings luxury through the experience of nature and history of place.

Here we can open our hearts to the light that magically brings in the turquoise Caribbean waters and shadows that dance across latticework and settle within seventeenth-century stone doorframes. 

There is much to discover.

This year, renowned interior designer, Barry Dixon, gave an emotional perspective around uncovering beauty and inspiration. “Looking at the beautiful things in nature you’re constantly connected with inspiration…By default you reprogram your brain to see the joyful and the beautiful things.”

He referenced a golden sliver of light among dark clouds and a mosquito’s form inspiring his Mosquito Chair.

He continued to deliver the message, “It is a joyous thing… Beauty is a feeling.” When you are looking for beauty, even subliminally, you ‘live’ in that world and you can bring that ‘joy’ to others.”

Magical things happen through beauty. They are discovered, they are cherished, and they bring joy.

~ Regina Sturrock

Sunday Places Notebook : Layers of the Aiken-Rhett House

Sunday is a quiet day of the week: a pause day. It’s a day of reflection that can bring fresh perspectives and ideas for the week ahead. On Sundays, I love to listen to old tunes; shed a wistful tear; smile; read; clean; fill my home with flowers; set my table with some meaningful odds-and-ends pieces; see beauty in the small and significant things around me; and often to pour over images from my far away and near-to-home journeys. It’s a notebook kind of  day that collects all the experiences and assembles them into beautiful packages. 

My ‘Sunday Places Notebook’ is an end-of-week post that is as much meant for me to enjoy as it is meant for you by bringing together the captures and perspectives that have shaped me as a creative and a person. 

From exotic architecture to the structure of a dandelion, these are random and thought-provoking recollections that are filled with inspiration. It represents a travel log where an iron street grate detail may take precedence over the iconic building or a where a butterfly wing may take focus over the picturesque landscape. 

Today, I revisit the raw and peeled-back beauty of what once was; a diamond-in-the -rough in reverse. 

This is a historical home in Charleston that I was fortunate to experience with Kravet Inc. and several Canadian designers. 

Showing all its intriguing layers, the Aiken-Rhett House is one of Charleston’s most renowned antebellum mansions. 

Without the polished veneers, this Greek Revival mansion is intensely beautiful in its historically layered and patinated form. There’s a magic here exposing a 150-year evolution of living, fashion, and technology. 

For me, the scenes opened my thoughts to the music that once played through harps, swirling dance caught and held within the carved frames of grand mirrors, and flowing dresses that presented the romance of the day as they descended alongside banister and carved spindle.

I’ve always been intrigued by secret doors, imagining the fantasy worlds behind them. Jib doors, as we call them in the design world, are fully integrated into the wall, panels, and mouldings and typically we use them to conceal function while maintaining the beauty of the architecture. Of course this example in the Queens Bed Chamber in the Palace of Versailles is an exuberant version. (I lingered for quite some time during my visit) The wallpaper and textiles are exquisite with peacock feathers and wisteria. Scroll through to see more historical opulence and craftsmanship. Certainly too adorned for today’s lifestyle but just one detail can inspire an entire room! It’s how the creative wheel turns through the centuries.

I love to write poetry.

I love to get my hands dirty in my  gardens up North and watch things grow and flourish. I love to design.

LUXURY: THE ART OF SEEING BEAUTY 

Luxury is seeing beauty and the appreciation of things that others may overlook. The subjective nature of beauty applies to all areas of our lives. It may be found in art, literature, music, or within the shifting scenes of a landscape. 

Beauty is in the eye of the beholder. We ask, ‘how do ‘we’ interpret it, how do ‘we’ see it, how do ‘we’ feel and understand it”.
World/famous art critic, Robert Studley Forrest Hughes, described the work of a favourite artist of mine, Daniele Rochon, as “part of a long project in art that reconciles us with the world, not by protest, irony, or political metaphors but ….by the ecstatic contemplation of pleasure in nature. It is not the world as it is but as our starved senses desire it to be; neither hostile, nor indifferent, but full of meaning.” 
Her own vision of her work ~ “My eye is never drawn toward the horizon but inside the wilderness, really deep inside.”

I feel that our perspectives of beauty, of art, and our eye-of-the-beholder views run parallel with this critique. It aligns with LUXURY as ‘we see it, how our senses desire it to be’ in our surroundings, in our home environments and even in our gardens. 

As an interior designer, I nurture the idea of bringing in meaningful art and collections to the homes of my clients. 

This is a luxury that I believe in with full heart. 

Bringing in a piece that represents the passion of a 
creator is powerful. 

But acquiring art is also about self-discovery ~ how we connect to the brush strokes, the colours, the energy, and the emotion while looking beyond the horizon and deep within. 

Art can come from a gallery or from a local artist whose work may not yet be recognized.  It may be a treasure discovered at a market among all other trinkets and wares. 

It’s a luxury accessible to all of us.

How do we create luxury? 

Part 3 of this series: 

Personalization and Tailoring is about~ 

Authenticity in design; genuine and real creations that work around the individual and that are part of their story. 

In order to achieve this, we need to come to a deeper understanding of who we’re creating for, what brings joy and fulfillment and how ‘best life’ can be realized. 

This is about a journey of self-discovery. 

When designing for our clients, we often 
put the mirror in front of them. Sometimes they simply aren’t aware or haven’t taken the time to get to the bottom of what it means to them or perhaps what that subliminal connection is that makes them feel good or what puts them at ease. And it’s easy to get sucked down the rabbit hole of inspiration these days. It often makes me cringe to realize that the path towards discovering beauty is being validated 
by what is found on Pinterest. Stop that! 

It’s important to us that the client is really invested in the process and feeds us with all the clues we need to embrace their passions and to build a luxury environment just for them and their lifestyle. 

This approach in design is thrilling to us because it’s where the magic happens, where we as creators stretch the boundaries, go well beyond the rules sometimes, but always manage to establish beauty. 

There is no formula or one-size-fits-all. No cut and paste. This we leave to the showroom floor. 

Customization is our mantra…. We look at it as a ‘tailoring to suit perfectly.’ It can carry the stigma of an unnecessary ‘extra’ but that’s not how we see it. It can convey a sense of rarity; uniqueness without saying ‘showy’ ‘or the pretentious display of how much was spent’. 

Whether it’s a creative ceiling detail 
that also manages to incorporate a unique indirect lighting system or a sleek and integrated built-in that also packs in maximum concealed storage or a creative way to hide a really large tv in an otherwise beautiful room, these are the ‘made-to-fit-perfectly’ details that we always bring.

PHOTO SHOOT 
1) The design journey can take years and especially when it’s a new build project so the photo shoot is a MILESTONE! It represents visions, many adjustments along the way, and dreams come true. AND PASSION for the craft. 
2) BEFORE the shoot there are weeks of preparation. This is when the magic unfolds with final touches and possibly with the addition of some missing links. An empty wall waiting for a special piece is often filled. The flowers and vases are readied and layers of beautiful books are placed. Can I tell you that this is a real exercise in defining the spirit of the home??! Yes, to see it all on the glossy pages is not the only goal. 
3)The NIGHT BEFORE flowers are waiting in coolers (when the wine cellar we created gets full use!) Most all has been positioned for the big day ahead and some lifestyle props are waiting to be delivered in the a.m. After all, what’s a kitchen without the elegant linen napkins and beautiful food displayed on large trays?! Not much sleep happens whilst lying in bed wondering if all has been accounted for. 
4) The BIG DAY. Hoping for a relatively cloudy day where bright streams of light can’t disrupt the flow. We start early! All has been placed before the photographer arrives (knowing that many things will be moved for each shot). The MUSIC is ON! To me, it’s part of each capture even if it can’t be seen. It can be felt. It’s part of the composition in my mind.
4) The WALK THROUGH. Together we decide the best plan in terms of natural light and when each space will be seen in its BEST LIGHT. Composition and angles are determined. How will the STORY be TOLD? I often give the photographer an insight to the space, elaborating on the details and how they came to be or pointing out the meaningful elements. 
5) SETTING up for the SHOT! So much to consider here both technically and artistically. All members of the shoot team are involved. The eyes see a space much differently than the camera so there are MANY minute ADJUSTMENTS while looking through the lens. 
Often the perfect arrangement of items is dismantled to achieve balance and the proper breathing room between elements.
YES! I think I LIKE IT!
